summary: I find it interesting that after years of the MCU being the dominant force in pop culture and so many other studios desperately...
body:
I find it interesting that after years of the MCU being the dominant force in pop culture and so many other studios desperately rushing to establish their own cinematic universes of popular franchises to compete, and most of these attempts falling short, it seems that right now, as Avengers Endgame (The culmination of everything Marvel has been building up to since before the Avengers even came out) is about to release, rival studios seem to finally be finding their groove.

Godzilla and Kong: Skull Island are both well received and successful movies and Godzilla: King of the Monsters has attracted a lot of buzz for looking like the Godzilla movie fans have been dreaming of their whole lives. So between that and Godzilla vs Kong coming up, the Monsterverse seems to be shaping up to be a smash hit.

Detective Pikachu, the first live action Pokémon movie, is coming out very soon and looks to be a smash hit in the making, and Legendary Entertainment has already confirmed they want to do a Pokémon Cinematic universe if it’s successful, with a sequel to the movie already announced.

And despite it’s terrible start with three badly received movies in a row, the DCEU has finally gotten it’s act together with Wonder Woman, Aquaman and Shazam all being well received hits.

And despite the Fox X-men film series being set to come to an end due to the Fox buyout, Sony clearly want to do an animated film series of Spider-man movies spinning off for Spider-Verse.

Heck, even Transformers looks like it might get a decent cinematic universe going with a reboot series thanks to the success of Bumblebee and Michael Bay finally being gone from the franchise hopefully for good.

Like, the timing of all of this stuff coming to pass is just very curious to me. Right as the MCU is at the end of it’s first major ongoing saga and getting ready to enter a whole new era is when it’s finally looking to get some serious competition in the Cinematic Universe business.

I’m definitely not one of the people that think the MCU is going to fall apart or that everybody’s going to start losing interest in it now that the Avengers movies are pretty much done, I think that’s simply not true and that the MCU is going to be around and successful for a long time.

But I am genuinely curious how the landscape of pop culture is going to look like a decade from now with all these other factors to consider.

Like, there’s a genuine possibility that by the 2030′s or whenever, the MCU might not be the undeniably biggest, center of pop culture franchise that it currently is seen as by much of the internet and general public, but just one among many big expansive film franchises. And maybe another series, like Pokémon, might be considered an even bigger deal.

I dunno, maybe I’m wrong, but I do think this is a very interesting time for pop culture and I’m interested to see how things progress going into the next decade.

body: You know, if Detective Pikachu does launch a Pokémon Cinematic Universe and they end up doing an adaption of the Gen 1 games plot… I kind of want them to use Ash as the main character instead of Red, if only because Legendary would have literally no choice but to let Ash age and grow up if they kept him around for several live-action movies.
